b:["$","div",null,{"className":"prose","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Who Should Choose Which?"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"The ideal user for each platform differs considerably. Make (Integromat) is best suited for power users, agencies, complex automations, making it a strong choice if you fall into any of these categories. Parabola, meanwhile, shines for operations teams, data analysts, e commerce, which means it may be the better pick if your needs align with those use cases.\n\nFounded in 2012, Make (Integromat) describes itself as \"Visual platform for designing, building, and automating complex workflows.\" Parabola, established in 2016, positions itself as \"Drag-and-drop data workflow automation for operations teams.\" Both platforms have been in the market for a similar duration, giving each ample time to refine their offerings and build a loyal user base."}]]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"verdict-box","children":[["$","h2",null,{"children":"Our Verdict"}],["$","p",null,{"children":"After analyzing all the data, **Make (Integromat)** comes out slightly ahead in this comparison, thanks to higher user ratings (9.0 vs 7.0), more features (10 vs 8), availability of a free plan. However, this does not mean Parabola is a poor choice — far from it. Parabola excels in its own right, particularly for operations teams and data analysts.\n\nOur recommendation: if you value superior visual workflow builder, go with Make (Integromat). If excellent for data transformation workflows matters more to you, Parabola is the way to go. Either way, both are solid platforms that have earned their place in the market."}]]}]
